The Familiar in the New Antisemitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors feel that emerging threats to Judaism are on the horizon, even before they become generally visible?
They know that the ostensibly "harmless" hints will turn into accusations and ultimately lead to discrimination, which is then legally entrenched.
At this point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm, because they know what's at stake.
That is how they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we can also survive.
Since the first round of the presidential elections in France, it is clear that we have a reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other rough right-wing extremists in Europe cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" were often the cheerleaders of Fascism or Communism, without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we're dealing with people - with the "educated bourgeoisie" connected to the mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often reminds one of the accomplices to these antidemocratic movements.
This is not about the majority opinion in the Western world - not yet, thankfully - but it is the voices of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to the United Kingdom should be mentioned: recently, he titled Israel as "this damned little country" during a dinner party in London.
His crude expression is not particularly frightening.
What's more alarming is the reaction to it.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the government demand his recall.  In the public eye, the matter was treated as just another scandal.
The French press presented the ambassador seriously as a victim of British gossip and not of his own contemptible attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to the United Kingdom has several allies among Europe's elites.
Ambassador Bernard, however, did us a service: Through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Semitic sentiments are.
As a columnist so aptly put it: Israel has become the hate object, whose name one dares not utter.
We, however, must not only dare to speak out, we are even obliged to express it.
Given the daily attacks against Jews and synagogues in France, we may not remain silent.
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without having to worry about their safety.
Antisemitic attacks are also reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and in parts of Eastern Europe.
We may not remain silent about the fact that the denial of the Holocaust is becoming commonplace. We may also not remain silent about the comparisons that antisemites and antizionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While in a Palestinian television broadcast Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we must "confront the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. Almost everyone hates them".
During the television broadcast of a Friday prayer in Palestinian television, the preacher called on Muslims to "show no mercy to Jews. Kill them wherever you are, and these Americans, who are just like them".
We should think about antisemitism in the context that it always starts with the Jews, but never ends with them.
If Jew hatred is not curbed, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore a task for Jews as well as non-Jews.
At present, the points of attack in this fight are less clear than ever before, because an astonishing aspect of today's antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism always remains the same - namely to attack Jews - it nevertheless changes its face, its strategy, its rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
In the past, the Jewish religion was the target.
When this did not give up, the Jews were expelled or killed.
As in the 19th century when the theory of race drew people under its spell, Jews were attacked because of their membership in a bad race.
With the existence of the State of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is being disparaged today as a racist ideology.
I don't equate criticism of Israel with anti-Semitism.
Just as with other nations, it is certainly legitimate to be critical of certain political strategies and decisions of Israel.
Anti-Zionism, however, is becoming increasingly similar to anti-Semitism.
Antizionists claim sometimes that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I'm only against the existence of Great Britain, but I'm not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
You wouldn't believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people, but to hate their state.
Yet there are people in connection with Israel who claim to be able to do exactly that.
Israel-bashing is on the agenda in different UN organizations.
This demonization of the only democratic state entity in the Near East is a key point of this new antisemitism.
If Israel is described as "the enemy of all that is good and the source of all evil," then the "doctrine of contempt" is circulating within the UN, as expressed by Professor Irwin Cotler, member of the Canadian parliament.
This permanent portrayal of a nation as an enemy of humanity is in fact a campaign against the Jewish people.
So are anti-Semitic attacks in many countries based on the demonization of Israel, which uses anti-Semitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this slanderous language in connection with the Middle East.
Compared to previous anti-Semitic outbreaks, today's anti-Semitism is less about attacks on individual Jews, and more about an attack against the "collective Jew," namely the State of Israel.
Such attacks, however, have set off a chain reaction of attacks on individual Jews and Jewish institutions across Europe and Latin America.
In the past, the most dangerous anti-Semites were those who wanted to make the world Jew-free.
The most dangerous anti-Semites of today are those who want to make the world Jew-state-free.
